ally, Geometrically and Hydrographically Explained by a New Method in ... a Complete Work Separated into 4 Tomes]</i>, Amsterdam: Apud Ioannem Ianssonium [by <a href="/wiki/Jan_Janszoon" title="Jan Janszoon">Jan Janszoon</a>]</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEdward+Wright+%28mathematician%29&amp;rft.au=Adriaan+Metius&amp;rft.btitle=Adriani+Metii+Alcmar+D.M.+et+matheseos+profess.+ordin.+Primum+mobile%3A+astronomic%C3%A8%2C+sciographic%C3%A8%2C+geometric%C3%A8%2C+et+hydrographic%C3%A8%2C+nova+methodo+explicatum+in+...+opus+absolutum%2C+IV+tomis+distinctum+%5B%26%2391%3BBy+Adrianus+Metius+of+Alkmaar%2C+ordained+Doctor+of+Medicine+and+professor+of+mathematics.%26%2393%3B+The+Primum+Mobile%3A+Astronomically%2C+Sciographically%2C+Geometrically+and+Hydrographically+Explained+by+a+New+Method+in+...+a+Complete+Work+Separated+into+4+Tomes%5D&amp;rft.date=1631&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.place=Amsterdam&amp;rft.pub=Apud+Ioannem+Ianssonium+%5Bby+Jan+Janszoon%5D&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span> (Latin). "Sciography", a variant of "sciagraphy", is the branch of the science of perspective dealing with the projection of shadows, or the art or practice of determining time by observing the shadow of the sun, moon or stars on a dial: <cite class="citation"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://dictionary.oed.com/cgi/entry/50215781">"sciagraphy"</a>, <i><a href="/wiki/Oxford_English_Dictionary" title="Oxford English Dictionary">OED Online</a></i> (2nd ed.), Oxford: <a href="/wiki/Oxford_University_Press" title="Oxford University Press">Oxford University Press</a>, 1989<span class="reference-accessdate">, retrieved <span class="nowrap">26 May</span> 2008</span></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEdward+Wright+%28mathematician%29&amp;rft.atitle=sciagraphy&amp;rft.btitle=OED+Online&amp;rft.date=1989&amp;rft.edition=2nd&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.place=Oxford&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fdictionary.oed.com%2Fcgi%2Fentry%2F50215781&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span><sup class="noprint Inline-Template"><span style="white-space: nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Link_rot" title="Wikipedia:Link rot"><span title="&#160;Dead link since July 2016">dead link</span></a></i>]</span></sup></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-53"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-53">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFRichard_Norwood1637" class="citation"><a href="/wiki/Richard_Norwood" title="Richard Norwood">Richard Norwood</a> (1637), <i>The Seaman\'s Practice, contayning a Fundamentall Probleme in Navigation Experimentally Verified; namely Touching the Compasse of the Earth and Sea, and the Quantity of a Degree in our English Measures. Also an Exact Method ... of Keeping a Reckoning at Sea; ... Tables, etc</i>, London: George Hurlock</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEdward+Wright+%28mathematician%29&amp;rft.au=Richard+Norwood&amp;rft.btitle=The+Seaman%27s+Practice%2C+contayning+a+Fundamentall+Probleme+in+Navigation+Experimentally+Verified%3B+namely+Touching+the+Compasse+of+the+Earth+and+Sea%2C+and+the+Quantity+of+a+Degree+in+our+English+Measures.+Also+an+Exact+Method+...+of+Keeping+a+Reckoning+at+Sea%3B+...+Tables%2C+etc&amp;rft.date=1637&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.place=London&amp;rft.pub=George+Hurlock&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-54"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-54">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFCharles_Saltonstall1636" class="citation">Charles Saltonstall (1636), <i>The Navigator, shewing and explaining